  "texts": [
    "Taking epidemic prevention and control as an example, epidemics usually break out in different regions.",
    "If the model lacks generalizability, it may lead to inaccurate prediction of the number of infections in different regions, thus affecting the rational allocation of medical resources (Wang et al. 2405; Panagopoulos et al. 2021).",
    "Therefore, improving the generalizability of graph pooling methods is of great significance to cope with such problems.",
    "In real-world application scenarios, graph data often exhibits a high degree of dynamics, in which nodes and edges change dynamically over time, such as the addition, deletion, and updating of nodes or edges (Zhu et al. 2023).",
    "Graph pooling, as a powerful data processing tool, must be able to flexibly adapt to these changes by simplifying the graph structure while retaining its core structural information and node features."
  ],
